instruction:
Create a `month` variable and assign any number between 1 and 12 to it.

Create a second variable `day` and assign any number from 1 to 31 to it.

Create a third variable `year` and assign any four-digit number to it.

Create a fourth variable `date` that will combine the first three variables into a single string
(make sure that all variables are separated from each other by a "/" character).

An example of a date in US format is `mm/dd/yyyyy` (month/day/year).

Create a fifth variable `dateLength`, which will show the length of the `date` variable.

Here is an example that is fundamentally similar to what you need to do,
but adapt it to the requirements of the task:
```javascript
const hours = 5;
const minutes = 30;
const seconds = 50;
const combinedString = hours + ':' + minutes + ':' + seconds;
const lengthOfCombinedString = combinedString.length;
```

hint:
```javascript
const month = 1;
const day = 24;
const year = 2020;
const date = month + '/' + day + '/' + year;
const dateLength = date.length;
```
